(66, 11, 14, 66, 8, 13, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Woes in Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of woe, indicating a sequence of judgments. Revelation 8:13 introduces the three woes, while Revelation 11:14 marks the completion of the second woe and the imminent arrival of the third.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 14, 66, 9, 12, 12, 'woe is past; and, behold,', 'Connection of Woes in Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the progression of woes, with Revelation 9:12 indicating that one woe has passed and two more are forthcoming, while Revelation 11:14 confirms that the second woe is past and the third is imminent. This connection highlights the sequential nature of the prophetic woes.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 14, 66, 15, 1, 1, 'the third woe cometh quickly', 'Connection of Woes and Plagues', 'This connection highlights the transition from the second woe to the introduction of the seven last plagues. Both passages emphasize the unfolding of God''s judgment, culminating in the final outpouring of His wrath.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 14, 66, 16, 1, 21, 'the third woe cometh quickly', 'Connection of Woes and Wrath', 'This connection highlights the progression of divine judgment, as the ''third woe'' in Revelation 11:14 anticipates the outpouring of God''s wrath in Revelation 16. Both passages emphasize the severity of God''s actions against those who oppose Him, culminating in catastrophic events.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 15, 27, 7, 14, 14, 'kingdoms of our Lord', 'Connection of Kingdoms and Dominion', 'Both passages emphasize the establishment of God''s everlasting kingdom. Revelation speaks of the kingdoms becoming the Lord''s, while Daniel describes His dominion as everlasting.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 15, 66, 12, 10, 10, 'kingdoms of our Lord, and of his Christ', 'Connection of Kingdoms and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the establishment of God''s kingdom and the reign of Christ. The first passage declares the kingdoms becoming His, while the second affirms the arrival of the kingdom of God and salvation.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 15, 27, 7, 27, 27, 'kingdoms of our Lord, and of his Christ', 'Connection of Kingdoms and Reign', 'Both passages emphasize the establishment of an everlasting kingdom. Revelation 11:15 declares the reign of Christ, while Daniel 7:27 speaks of the kingdom given to the saints. This connection highlights the ultimate sovereignty of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 15, 66, 10, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of the Seventh Angel', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the seventh angel in the unfolding of God''s plan. Revelation 10:7 indicates that the mystery of God will be finished at the sounding of the seventh angel, which is fulfilled in Revelation 11:15 when the kingdoms become the Lord''s.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 15, 38, 14, 9, 9, NULL, 'Kingship of the Lord', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s sovereignty over all kingdoms. Both passages emphasize the reign of the Lord, indicating a future time when He will be king over all the earth.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 15, 42, 1, 33, 33, 'he shall reign for ever and ever', 'Eternal Reign of Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s eternal reign in both passages. Revelation 11:15 declares that Christ will reign forever, paralleling Luke 1:33''s assertion that his kingdom will have no end.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 15, 2, 15, 18, 18, 'he shall reign for ever and ever', 'Eternal Reign of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the eternal reign of the Lord. Revelation 11:15 declares that the kingdoms of the world belong to the Lord, while Exodus 15:18 states that the Lord shall reign forever.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 16, 66, 4, 4, 4, 'twenty elders', 'Elders Worship Before God', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of the twenty-four elders before God''s throne. In Revelation 4:4, they are described as sitting on seats, while in Revelation 11:16, they fall upon their faces in worship, highlighting their reverence and authority in God''s presence.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 16, 66, 4, 10, 10, 'fell upon their faces, and worshipped God', 'Elders Worshiping God', 'Both passages emphasize the act of the four and twenty elders falling down and worshiping God. This connection highlights the reverence and adoration shown by the elders in the presence of the divine.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 16, 66, 7, 11, 11, 'fell upon their faces, and worshipped God', 'Worship Before the Throne', 'Both passages emphasize the act of worship before God, with figures falling on their faces in reverence. This connection highlights a shared theme of humility and adoration in the heavenly realm.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 16, 66, 5, 14, 14, 'fell upon their faces, and worshipped God', 'Worship of the Elders', 'Both passages emphasize the act of worship by the twenty-four elders before God. The phrase ''fell down and worshipped'' in Revelation 5:14 is mirrored in Revelation 11:16, highlighting a consistent theme of reverence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 16, 66, 19, 4, 4, 'fell upon their faces, and worshipped God', 'Worship of God by Elders', 'Both passages emphasize the act of worship by the four and twenty elders. In each instance, they fall down and worship God, highlighting a consistent theme of reverence and adoration in the presence of the divine.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 16, 66, 5, 5, 8, 'fell upon their faces, and worshipped God', 'Worship of God and the Lamb', 'Both passages emphasize the act of worship by the elders. In Revelation 11:16, the elders worship God, while in Revelation 5:8, they fall down before the Lamb, indicating a shared reverence. This connection highlights the continuity of worship in the heavenly realm.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 17, 66, 1, 8, 8, NULL, 'Divine Sovereignty and Eternity', 'Both passages emphasize God''s eternal nature and sovereignty. They highlight His existence in the past, present, and future, underscoring His reign and power.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 17, 66, 16, 5, 5, 'which art, and wast, and art to come', 'Divine Attributes and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the eternal nature of God with the phrases ''which art, and wast, and art to come'' and ''which art, and wast, and shalt be.'' Additionally, they highlight God''s sovereignty, with Revelation 11:17 acknowledging His reign and Revelation 16:5 affirming His righteousness in judgment.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 17, 19, 21, 13, 13, 'thy great power', 'Exaltation of God''s Power', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of praising God''s power and strength. Revelation 11:17 acknowledges God''s reign and power, while Psalms 21:13 calls for exaltation and praise of that power.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 17, 1, 17, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of God as ''Almighty.'' Revelation acknowledges God''s reign and power, while Genesis introduces God as ''Almighty'' in His covenant with Abram. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s authority throughout scripture.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 17, 23, 51, 9, 11, 'great power, and hast reigned', 'Divine Power and Redemption', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s power and reign in both passages. Revelation 11:17 speaks of God taking great power and reigning, while Isaiah 51:9-11 recalls His mighty acts and promises of redemption for His people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 17, 54, 1, 12, 12, 'We give thee thanks, O Lord God Almighty', 'Thankfulness to God', 'This connection highlights the theme of gratitude expressed in both passages. Revelation 11:17 thanks God for His reign, while 1 Timothy 1:12 expresses thanks to Christ Jesus for enabling ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 17, 19, 57, 11, 11, 'O Lord God Almighty', 'Exaltation of God', 'Both passages emphasize the greatness and sovereignty of God. Revelation 11:17 acknowledges God''s reign and power, while Psalms 57:11 calls for God''s glory to be exalted above the heavens and earth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 18, 66, 19, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Praise and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God''s servants and those who fear Him, highlighting their significance in the context of divine judgment and reward. The mention of ''small and great'' in both verses underscores the inclusivity of God''s recognition.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 18, 66, 20, 12, 12, NULL, 'Judgment of the Dead', 'Both passages emphasize the judgment of the dead, highlighting that all will stand before God to be judged according to their works. The mention of ''the dead, small and great'' in both verses reinforces this theme of universal accountability.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 18, 19, 103, 11, 11, 'them that fear thy name', 'Connection of Mercy and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of mercy toward those who fear God. Revelation speaks of rewards for the faithful, while Psalms highlights God''s mercy for those who fear Him.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 18, 19, 115, 13, 14, 'small and great', 'Connection of Blessings and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of blessings for those who fear the Lord, highlighting the contrast between the faithful and those who destroy the earth. The mention of ''small and great'' in both verses reinforces this connection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 18, 33, 7, 15, 17, 'the nations were angry', 'Judgment and Fear of Nations', 'Both passages emphasize the response of nations to God''s judgment. Revelation speaks of the nations'' anger and the coming wrath, while Micah describes the nations being confounded and afraid of the Lord. This connection highlights the theme of divine retribution and the fear it instills in the nations.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 18, 58, 11, 25, 26, NULL, 'Connection of Reward and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of reward for faithfulness and the consequences of choices. Revelation speaks of giving reward to God''s servants, while Hebrews highlights the value of suffering for Christ over earthly treasures, pointing to a future recompense.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 18, 23, 34, 1, 10, 'thy wrath is come', 'Judgment and Vengeance Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the Lord''s wrath and judgment against the nations. Revelation 11:18 speaks of the time for the dead to be judged, while Isaiah 34:1-10 describes the Lord''s indignation and vengeance upon all nations.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 19, 66, 16, 21, 21, 'great hail', 'Hail as Divine Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the occurrence of great hail as a sign of divine judgment. The hail in Revelation 16:21 follows the heavenly scene in Revelation 11:19, linking the two as manifestations of God''s power.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 19, 26, 38, 22, 22, 'great hail', 'Connection of Divine Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the themes of divine judgment and catastrophic events. Revelation describes the temple''s opening with great hail, while Ezekiel mentions great hailstones as part of God''s judgment.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 19, 66, 15, 5, 8, 'the temple of God was opened in heaven', 'Connection of Heavenly Temple Visions', 'Both passages emphasize the opening of the temple in heaven, revealing significant divine elements. The first passage introduces the ark of the testament, while the second describes the temple of the tabernacle of the testimony, linking them through their heavenly significance.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(66, 11, 19, 23, 30, 30, 30, 'lightnings, and voices, and thunderings', 'Divine Voice and Natural Phenomena', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of divine power through natural phenomena such as lightnings, tempests, and hail. This connection highlights the dramatic manifestations of God''s voice and anger in both texts.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
